⍝ UTF Probe Test: demonstrates T1 vs UTF8 vs T2 differences
⍝ This script passes the same string through different ⎕NA type declarations
⍝ and logs what the C function actually receives.

dll←'D:\devel\Z-Format\probe\utf_probe'

⍝ Delete old log (ignore if doesn't exist)
:Trap 0
    ⎕NDELETE (2 ⎕NQ '.' 'GetEnvironment' 'TEMP'),'\utf_probe_log.txt'
:EndTrap

⍝ === Test 1: T1 (raw bytes, no encoding) ===
⍝ T1[] means null-terminated 1-byte char array
'pt1' ⎕NA dll,'|probe_t1 <0T1[] I'
⍝ 'café' has 'é' = U+00E9
s←'café'
pt1 s (≢s)
⎕←'T1 test done: ',⍕≢s,' chars sent'

⍝ === Test 2: UTF8 (interpreter encodes to UTF-8) ===
'putf8' ⎕NA dll,'|probe_utf8 <0UTF8[] I'
putf8 s (4+1)  ⍝ UTF-8 encodes 'é' as 2 bytes → 5 bytes total + null
⎕←'UTF8 test done'

⍝ === Test 3: T2 (raw 16-bit codepoints, Windows wchar_t) ===
'pt2' ⎕NA dll,'|probe_t2 <0T2[] I'
pt2 s (≢s)
⎕←'T2 test done'

⍝ === Test 4: UTF8 with multi-byte characters ===
⍝ '日本語' = U+65E5 U+672C U+8A9E (3 chars, 9 bytes in UTF-8)
s2←'日本語'
putf8 s2 (9)
⎕←'UTF8 CJK test done: ',⍕≢s2,' chars → 9 UTF-8 bytes'

⍝ === Test 5: T1 with high codepoints (DOMAIN ERROR!) ===
⍝ T1 cannot pass characters with codepoints > 255
:Trap 11  ⍝ DOMAIN ERROR
    pt1 s2 (≢s2)
    ⎕←'T1 CJK: unexpectedly succeeded'
:Else
    ⎕←'T1 CJK: DOMAIN ERROR (as expected — T1 rejects codepoints > 255)'
:EndTrap

⎕←''
⎕←'Check log: %TEMP%\utf_probe_log.txt'
